1. Create Docker file to package the application.
    - minimal base image python:3.12-slim or alpine.
    - Applicaion must not run as the root user.
    - use gunicorn as the production WSGI server.

2. Create YAML or Helm CHart for deployment
    - Deployment 1 + replicas, incuding Resource Limits (CPU/MEMORY) and liveness/readiness probes
    - Service A ClusterIP service to expose application internally on port 8080

3. Access the application from your host machine's browser
    - Use kubectl port-forward command to map a local port to the service or pod
    - Validation: provide a screenshot or curl output showing a successful response from http://localhost:<your-port>

4. Bonus Challenges (Optional)

For extra credit, implement one or more of the following:

Ingress Implementation: Configure an Ingress resource to map the hostname devops.test to your service. Include instructions for local DNS mapping.
Monitoring & Observability: Demonstrate how you would monitor this application (e.g., Prometheus metrics, structured logging, or a simple sidecar container).


Command Used:
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml 
kubectl apply -f ingress.yaml   
kubectl port-forward service/devops-service 8080:8080 

I used python:3.12-slim because it is the official Python image and it keeps the container
lean without making the environment unnecessarily fragile. 
For security, I made sure the app does not run as root, enforced non-root execution again in Kubernetes,
disabled privilege escalation, and dropped all capabilities.
Since this service only needs to serve HTTP traffic on port 8080, anything beyond that would be unnecessary privilege.